<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-confidence-intervals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Confidence Intervals</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>In statistics, we usually care about a whole population but only get
    to see a sample. That means we need methods for using sample information
    to say something sensible about unknown population quantities.</p>
    <p>This chapter focuses on estimating three common kinds of
    parameters: a population mean, a population proportion, and a population
    variance. The main tool is the <term>confidence interval<idx><h>inference</h><h>confidence
    interval</h></idx></term>, which gives a range of plausible values for
    the parameter. To justify those formulas, we first need to understand
    how sample means, sample proportions, and sample variances behave.</p>
    <p>For means and proportions, the normal distribution does most of the
    work. For variance and standard deviation from a normal population, the
    chi-square distribution is the key player instead.</p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-sampling-distributions-clt">
    <title>Sampling Distributions and the CLT</title>
    <shorttitle>Sampling Distributions and the CLT</shorttitle>

    <p>Suppose a population has mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation
    <m>\sigma</m>. If we draw a sample of size <m>n</m>, then the <term>sample
    mean<idx><h>data</h><h>sample mean</h></idx></term> is</p>

    <me>
      \overline{X}=\frac{X_1+X_2+\cdots+X_n}{n}.
    </me>

    <p>The variable <m>\overline{X}</m> is itself a random
    variable. Its distribution is called a <term>sampling
    distribution<idx><h>inference</h><h>sampling
    distribution</h></idx></term>.</p>

    <p>Two facts are especially important:</p>

    <me>
      E(\overline{X})=\mu \qquad\text{and}\qquad
      \sigma_{\overline{X}}=\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>These formulas follow directly from the properties of expectation
    and variance from <xref ref="sec-cdf-expected-value"/>. Since</p>

    <me>
      \overline{X}=\frac{X_1+X_2+\cdots+X_n}{n},
    </me>

    <p>linearity of expectation gives</p>

    <me>
      E(\overline{X}) =E\left(\frac{X_1+\cdots+X_n}{n}\right)
      =\frac{1}{n}\bigl(E(X_1)+\cdots+E(X_n)\bigr) =\frac{1}{n}(n\mu) =\mu.
    </me>

    <p>So the sample mean is an unbiased estimate of the population mean.</p>

    <p>For the variance, independence lets us add variances:</p>

    <md alignment="align">
      <mrow>\operatorname{Var}(\overline{X})&amp;=\operatorname{Var}\left(\frac{X_1+\cdots+X_n}{n}\right)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;=\frac{1}{n^2}\operatorname{Var}(X_1+\cdots+X_n)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;=\frac{1}{n^2}\bigl(\operatorname{Var}(X_1)+\cdots+\operatorname{Var}(X_n)\bigr).</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Because each <m>X_i</m> has variance <m>\sigma^2</m>,</p>

    <me>
      \operatorname{Var}(\overline{X})
      =\frac{1}{n^2}(n\sigma^2)
      =\frac{\sigma^2}{n}.
    </me>

    <p>Taking square roots gives</p>

    <me>
      \sigma_{\overline{X}}=\sqrt{\operatorname{Var}(\overline{X})}
      =\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^2}{n}}
      =\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>The first fact says that the sample mean is centered at the population
    mean. The second says that larger samples give less variation. Averaging
    many observations produces a more stable estimate than using just one
    observation.</p>

    <p>The real breakthrough is the <term>Central Limit
    Theorem<idx><h>inference</h><h>Central Limit Theorem</h></idx></term>,
    usually shortened to CLT. In plain language, it says this:</p>

    <p>If we repeatedly take independent samples from the same population,
    then for large <m>n</m> the distribution of the sample means becomes
    approximately normal, even if the original population is not normal.</p>

    <p>More precisely, when the observations are independent and identically
    distributed with mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>,
    the sample mean <m>\overline{X}</m> is approximately distributed as</p>

    <me>
      \overline{X}\sim N\left(\mu,\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)
    </me>

    <p>for large enough <m>n</m>.</p>

    <p>This theorem is a big deal. It explains why the normal distribution
    keeps showing up in statistics. Even when the raw data are skewed or
    irregular, the average of a reasonably large sample often behaves in a
    nearly normal way.</p>

    <p>A common rule of thumb is that <m>n\ge 30</m> is often enough, though
    very skewed populations may need larger samples. The sample should also
    come from an independent process, which is usually reasonable when we
    sample with replacement or sample from a population much larger than
    the sample size.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-clt-wait-times">
      <title>Using the CLT for a Sample Mean</title> <p>Suppose customer
      wait times have population mean 18 minutes and population standard
      deviation 6 minutes. The shape of the population distribution is not
      known. If we take a random sample of <m>n=36</m> customers, then by
      the CLT the sample mean is approximately normal:</p> <me>
        \overline{X}\sim N\left(18,\frac{6}{\sqrt{36}}\right)=N(18,1).
      </me> <p>The probability that the sample mean is less than 17 minutes
      is therefore</p> <me>
        P(\overline{X}&lt;17)=P\!\left(Z&lt;\frac{17-18}{1}\right)=P(Z&lt;-1)\approx
        0.1587.
      </me>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="ci-inline-ex-1">
      <p>A population has mean 50 and standard deviation 12. A sample of size 36 is taken.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Find the mean of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find the standard deviation of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>State the approximate distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> using the CLT.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-sample-mean-sprint">
      <title>Sample Mean Sprint</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>See how the spread of sample means changes as the sample size grows.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A population has mean 50 and standard deviation 12. Find the mean and standard deviation of <m>\overline{X}</m> for sample sizes <m>n=4</m>, <m>n=16</m>, and <m>n=36</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Which sample size gives the most stable sample mean, and why?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>If the population is strongly skewed, what does the CLT say about the shape of the sampling distribution when <m>n</m> is large?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-clt-sketchbook">
      <title>CLT Sketchbook</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Draw the idea of the Central Limit Theorem instead of only writing formulas.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Sketch a population distribution that is strongly right-skewed. Label the sketch with a few sample values that might come from it.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Sketch what the distribution of sample means might look like for samples of size 5 and for samples of size 40.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Explain in words how the center and spread of the sampling distribution compare with the original population.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-confidence-intervals-mean">
    <title>Confidence Intervals for the Mean</title>

    <p>A sample mean <m>\overline{x}</m> is a <term>point
    estimate<idx><h>inference</h><h>point estimate</h></idx></term> of
    the population mean <m>\mu</m>. But a single number does not tell us
    how much uncertainty comes from sampling. A <m>C</m> <term>confidence
    interval<idx><h>inference</h><h>confidence interval</h></idx></term> adds a
    margin of error to the point estimate and gives a range of plausible
    values for <m>\mu</m>, where <m>0 \lt C \lt 1</m> is the <term>confidence
    level<idx><h>inference</h><h>confidence level</h></idx></term>. In
    informal language, we say we are <m>C</m> confident that the resulting
    interval captures the true mean.</p>

    <p>To see where the formula comes from, suppose <m>X_1,\ldots,X_n</m> are
    iid with mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>, and
    suppose the standardized sample mean has a standard normal distribution
    (exactly when the population is normal, or approximately for large
    samples by the CLT):</p>

    <me>
      \frac{\overline{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}} \sim N(0,1).
    </me>

    <p>Let <m>\alpha=1-C</m>. To capture the middle proportion <m>C</m> of the
    standard normal curve, we leave total area <m>\alpha</m> outside and split
    it evenly between the two tails. That is, each tail has area
    <m>\alpha/2</m>.</p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ci-central-area">
      <caption>The middle <m>C</m> of the standard normal curve</caption>
      <image width="76%" margins="12%">
        
      <shortdescription>A standard normal curve with the central region
      between negative z-alpha-over-2 and positive z-alpha-over-2 shaded
      and labeled C. Each tail outside that region is labeled alpha over
      2.</shortdescription>
        <description>The graphic shows the standard normal density curve
        centered at 0. Vertical dashed lines mark the cutoff points at negative
        z-alpha-over-2 and positive z-alpha-over-2. The region under the curve
        between these two lines is shaded and labeled C. The two unshaded tails
        outside the dashed lines are each labeled alpha over 2, showing that
        the total area outside the center is alpha.</description> 
	<latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
              width=10cm,
              height=6cm,
              xmin=-3.5,
              xmax=3.5,
              ymin=0,
              ymax=0.45,
              axis lines=left,
              xlabel={$z$},
              ylabel={},
              xtick={-1.96,0,1.96},
              xticklabels={$-z_{\alpha/2}$,$0$,$z_{\alpha/2}$},
              ytick=\empty,
              enlargelimits=false,
              clip=false
            ]
              \addplot[
                draw=none,
                fill=blue!25,
                domain=-1.96:1.96,
                samples=160
              ]
              {1/sqrt(2*3.14159)*exp(-x^2/2)} \closedcycle;

              \addplot[
                thick,
                domain=-3.5:3.5,
                samples=240,
                color=black
              ]
              {1/sqrt(2*3.14159)*exp(-x^2/2)};

              \addplot[
                dashed,
                color=black
              ]
              coordinates {(-1.96,0) (-1.96,{1/sqrt(2*3.14159)*exp(-(1.96)^2/2)})};

              \addplot[
                dashed,
                color=black
              ]
              coordinates {(1.96,0) (1.96,{1/sqrt(2*3.14159)*exp(-(1.96)^2/2)})};

              \node at (axis cs:0,0.17) {$C$};
              \node at (axis cs:-2.65,0.06) {$\alpha/2$};
              \node at (axis cs:2.65,0.06) {$\alpha/2$};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>So the corresponding probability statement is</p>

    <me>
      P\left(-z_{\alpha/2} \lt \frac{\overline{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}} \lt z_{\alpha/2}\right)=C.
    </me>

    <p>After we collect the sample and observe <m>\overline{x}</m>, we solve
    that inequality for <m>\mu</m>. The result is the z-interval</p>

    <me>
      \overline{x}\pm z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}},
    </me>

    <p>or, written as an interval,</p>

    <me>
      \left(\overline{x}-z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}},\;
      \overline{x}+z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right).
    </me>

    <p>In practice, <m>\sigma</m> is often unknown. When the sample is large,
    we usually replace <m>\sigma</m> by the sample standard deviation
    <m>s</m> and still use the z critical value as an approximation. When the
    sample is small and the population is normal, we use a z-interval if
    <m>\sigma</m> is known, but if <m>\sigma</m> is unknown and we replace it
    by <m>s</m>, then</p>

    <me>
      \frac{\overline{X}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}} \sim t[n-1].
    </me>

    <p>In every case, the confidence interval has the form
    point estimate <m>\pm</m> margin of error. For the population mean, that
    means</p>

    <me>
    (\overline{x}-\text{margin of error},\overline{x}+\text{margin of error}),
    </me>

    <p>So the interval is centered at a sample mean, and its total width is
    twice the margin of error.</p>

    <p>We summarize the confidence-interval settings for a population mean
    in <xref ref="tbl-ci-summary"/>.</p>

    <table xml:id="tbl-ci-summary">
      <title>Sampling distributions and confidence intervals for a mean</title>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell>Setting</cell>
          <cell>Statistic</cell>
          <cell>Margin</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>n\ge 30</m>, <m>\sigma</m> known</cell>
          <cell><m>\frac{\overline{x}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\sim N(0,1)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>n\ge 30</m>, <m>\sigma</m> unknown</cell>
          <cell><m>\frac{\overline{x}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}}\sim N(0,1)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>z_{\alpha/2}\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>n&lt;30</m>, normal, <m>\sigma</m> known</cell>
          <cell><m>\frac{\overline{x}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\sim N(0,1)</m></cell>
          <cell><m>z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="major">
          <cell><m>n&lt;30</m>, normal, <m>\sigma</m> unknown</cell>
          <cell><m>\frac{\overline{x}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}}\sim t[n-1]</m></cell>
          <cell><m>t_{\alpha/2}[n-1]\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <p>The next four examples illustrate these four cases.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-z-ci-height">
      <title>Case 1: Large Sample, <m>\sigma</m> Known</title>
      <p>Suppose a sample of 36 women has mean height <m>\overline{x}=65.1</m> inches. Assume the population standard deviation is known to be 2.8 inches. A 95% confidence interval for the mean height is</p>
      <me>
        65.1\pm 1.96\frac{2.8}{\sqrt{36}}=65.1\pm 0.9147.
      </me>
      <p>So the interval is</p>
      <me>
        (64.1853,66.0147).
      </me>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-z-ci-large-unknown">
      <title>Case 2: Large Sample, <m>\sigma</m> Unknown</title>
      <p>A random sample of 64 delivery times has mean <m>\overline{x}=72.4</m> minutes and sample standard deviation <m>s=12</m> minutes. Find a 95% confidence interval for the population mean.</p>
      <p>Because the sample is large, we use the z critical value and replace <m>\sigma</m> by <m>s</m>:</p>
      <me>
        \overline{x}\pm z_{0.025}\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}
        =72.4\pm 1.96\frac{12}{\sqrt{64}}
        =72.4\pm 2.94.
      </me>
      <p>So the confidence interval is</p>
      <me>
        (69.46,75.34).
      </me>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-z-ci-small-known">
      <title>Case 3: Small Sample, Population Normal, <m>\sigma</m> Known</title>
      <p>Assume the population distribution is normal. A sample of size 16 has mean <m>\overline{x}=50</m>, and the population standard deviation is known to be <m>\sigma=4</m>. Find a 90% confidence interval for the population mean.</p>
      <p>Because the population is normal and <m>\sigma</m> is known, we use a z interval:</p>
      <me>
        \overline{x}\pm z_{0.05}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}
        =50\pm 1.645\frac{4}{\sqrt{16}}
        =50\pm 1.645.
      </me>
      <p>So the confidence interval is</p>
      <me>
        (48.355,51.645).
      </me>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-t-ci-small-sample">
      <title>Case 4: Small Sample, Population Normal, <m>\sigma</m> Unknown</title>
      <p>Assume the population is normal. A sample of 11 observations has sample mean <m>\overline{x}=8.8636</m> and sample standard deviation <m>s=1.3223</m>. For a 95% confidence interval, we use <m>df=10</m> and <m>t_{0.025}[10]=2.228</m>.</p>
      <p>The margin of error is</p>
      <me>
        2.228\frac{1.3223}{\sqrt{11}}\approx 0.8883.
      </me>
      <p>So the confidence interval is</p>
      <me>
        (8.8636-0.8883,\;8.8636+0.8883)=(7.9753,9.7519).
      </me>
    </example>

    <p>Interpreting a confidence interval takes some care. Before we collect
    the data, the sample mean <m>\overline{X}</m> is random, so the interval
    built from it is random too. In that stage, it is correct to say that the
    interval procedure has probability 0.95 of capturing <m>\mu</m>.</p>

    <p>After we collect the sample and get a specific value
    <m>\overline{x}</m>, the interval becomes a fixed interval with fixed
    endpoints. At that point, the true mean <m>\mu</m> is either inside the
    interval or it is not. So a 95% confidence level does not mean there is a
    95% chance that <m>\mu</m> is in this one computed interval. It means that
    if we repeated the same sampling process many times and built an interval
    each time, about 95% of those intervals would capture the true mean. The
    parameter <m>\mu</m> is fixed; the interval is what changes from sample to
    sample.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="ci-inline-ex-2">
      <p>A sample of size 49 has mean <m>\overline{x}=82</m>. Assume the population standard deviation is known to be 14.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Write the formula for a 90% confidence interval for <m>\mu</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find the margin of error.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find the interval.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-confidence-builder">
      <title>Confidence Interval Builder</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Build a confidence interval from a sample mean and a known population standard deviation.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A sample of size 49 has mean <m>\overline{x}=82</m>. Assume the population standard deviation is 14. Find a 90% confidence interval for <m>\mu</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Find the margin of error and interpret it in context.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Explain what the confidence level means in this situation.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-interval-faceoff">
      <title>Interval Face-Off</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Compare confidence intervals made from the same sample but with different confidence levels.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Using the same sample from the previous activity, compare the width of a 90% interval and a 95% interval.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Which interval is wider, and why does that happen?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>If a student wants a narrower interval, should they ask for higher confidence or lower confidence?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-confidence-intervals-proportion">
    <title>Confidence Intervals for a Population Proportion</title>

    <p>Many statistical questions are really yes-or-no questions. What
    proportion of voters support a ballot measure? What proportion of
    products coming off an assembly line are defective? What proportion of
    students at a college work more than 20 hours per week? In settings like
    these, the parameter we want is the <term>population
    proportion<idx><h>inference</h><h>population proportion</h></idx></term>,
    usually written <m>p</m>.</p>

    <p>If we take a random sample of size <m>n</m> and count the number of
    successes, say <m>X</m>, then a natural estimate of <m>p</m> is the
    <term>sample proportion<idx><h>data</h><h>sample
    proportion</h></idx></term>:</p>

    <me>
      \widehat{p}=\frac{X}{n}.
    </me>

    <p>This section is built directly on the binomial model from
    <xref ref="sec-binomial-normal-approximation"/>. If each observation is a
    success or failure, and the success probability is <m>p</m>, then the
    count <m>X</m> of successes in <m>n</m> independent trials has a binomial
    distribution:</p>

    <me>
      X\sim B(n,p).
    </me>

    <p>From the binomial chapter, for large enough <m>n</m> we can approximate
    this binomial count by a normal random variable with the same mean and
    standard deviation:</p>

    <me>
      X \approx N(np,\sqrt{np(1-p)}),
    </me>

    <p>provided the expected numbers of successes and failures are both at
    least about 5:</p>

    <me>
      np\ge 5
      \qquad\text{and}\qquad
      n(1-p)\ge 5.
    </me>

    <p>Now divide everything by <m>n</m>. Since <m>\widehat{p}=X/n</m>, the
    sample proportion is approximately normal with mean</p>

    <me>
      E(\widehat{p})=E\left(\frac{X}{n}\right)=\frac{E(X)}{n}=\frac{np}{n}=p
    </me>

    <p>and standard deviation</p>

    <me>
      \sigma_{\widehat{p}}
      =\frac{\sigma_X}{n}
      =\frac{\sqrt{np(1-p)}}{n}
      =\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>So for large samples,</p>

    <me>
      \widehat{p}\approx N\left(p,\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}\right).
    </me>

    <p>That is the key fact behind a one-proportion confidence interval. Once
    we standardize, we get the approximate z-statistic</p>

    <me>
      \frac{\widehat{p}-p}{\sqrt{p(1-p)/n}} \approx N(0,1).
    </me>

    <p>Let <m>\alpha=1-C</m> as before. Then the middle proportion <m>C</m> of
    the standard normal curve gives</p>

    <me>
      P\left(
      -z_{\alpha/2}
      \lt
      \frac{\widehat{p}-p}{\sqrt{p(1-p)/n}}
      \lt
      z_{\alpha/2}
      \right)\approx C.
    </me>

    <p>Solving that inequality for <m>p</m> suggests the interval</p>

    <me>
      \widehat{p}\pm z_{\alpha/2}\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>There is one catch: the standard deviation still contains the unknown
    parameter <m>p</m>. In practice we plug in the sample proportion
    <m>\widehat{p}</m> in its place. That gives the usual large-sample
    confidence interval for a population proportion:</p>

    <me>
      \widehat{p}\pm z_{\alpha/2}\sqrt{\frac{\widehat{p}(1-\widehat{p})}{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>So the margin of error for a proportion is</p>

    <me>
      E=z_{\alpha/2}\sqrt{\frac{\widehat{p}(1-\widehat{p})}{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>This method works well when the sample is random or otherwise
    independent, and when the sample is large enough that the observed counts
    of successes and failures are both at least about 5:</p>

    <me>
      n\widehat{p}\ge 5
      \qquad\text{and}\qquad
      n(1-\widehat{p})\ge 5.
    </me>

    <p>If sampling is done without replacement from a finite population, a
    common rule of thumb is that the population should be at least 10 times as
    large as the sample so the observations are close to independent.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-ci-proportion-campus-poll">
      <title>A Confidence Interval for Support in a Campus Poll</title>
      <p>A random sample of 200 students is asked whether they support a new
      campus tutoring center. Suppose 124 students say yes. Estimate the
      population proportion <m>p</m> of all students who support the plan with
      95% confidence.</p>

      <p>Here <m>x=124</m>, <m>n=200</m>, so</p>

      <me>
        \widehat{p}=\frac{124}{200}=0.62.
      </me>

      <p>The large-sample conditions are met because</p>

      <me>
        n\widehat{p}=200(0.62)=124
        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
        n(1-\widehat{p})=200(0.38)=76,
      </me>

      <p>and both numbers are much larger than 5. For 95% confidence,
      <m>z_{0.025}=1.96</m>. The margin of error is</p>

      <me>
        E=1.96\sqrt{\frac{0.62(0.38)}{200}}\approx 0.0673.
      </me>

      <p>So the confidence interval is</p>

      <me>
        0.62\pm 0.0673=(0.5527,0.6873).
      </me>

      <p>So we estimate that between about 55.3% and 68.7% of all students
      support the tutoring center.</p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-ci-proportion-defects">
      <title>A Confidence Interval for a Defect Rate</title>
      <p>A quality-control inspector checks 400 light bulbs and finds 18
      defective ones. Find a 90% confidence interval for the population
      proportion of defective bulbs.</p>

      <p>First compute the sample proportion:</p>

      <me>
        \widehat{p}=\frac{18}{400}=0.045.
      </me>

      <p>The large-sample conditions are satisfied because</p>

      <me>
        n\widehat{p}=400(0.045)=18
        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
        n(1-\widehat{p})=400(0.955)=382.
      </me>

      <p>For 90% confidence, <m>z_{0.05}=1.645</m>. The margin of error is</p>

      <me>
        E=1.645\sqrt{\frac{0.045(0.955)}{400}}\approx 0.0170.
      </me>

      <p>So the confidence interval is</p>

      <me>
        0.045\pm 0.0170=(0.0280,0.0620).
      </me>

      <p>That puts the defect rate at about 2.8% to 6.2%.</p>
    </example>

    <p>The interpretation follows the same pattern as for means. A 95%
    confidence interval for <m>p</m> does not mean there is a 95% chance that
    the fixed population proportion is inside the one interval we already
    computed. It means that if we repeated the sampling process many times and
    built an interval each time, about 95% of those intervals would capture
    the true proportion.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="ci-inline-ex-3">
      <p>In a random sample of 150 customers, 57 say they used a store coupon
      that week.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Find <m>\widehat{p}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Check whether the large-sample conditions for a one-proportion z-interval are met.</p></li>
        <li><p>Write the formula for a 95% confidence interval for <m>p</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-proportion-builder">
      <title>Proportion Interval Builder</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Build a confidence interval for a population proportion from a sample count.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A random sample of 120 students finds that 48 prefer digital notes to printed notes. Compute <m>\widehat{p}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Check whether the conditions for a one-proportion z-interval are satisfied.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Find a 95% confidence interval for the population proportion and interpret it in context.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-approximation-check">
      <title>Can We Trust the Approximation?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Decide when the normal approximation behind a proportion interval is reasonable.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>For each pair <m>(n,\widehat{p})</m>, compute <m>n\widehat{p}</m> and <m>n(1-\widehat{p})</m>: <m>(40,0.10)</m>, <m>(80,0.55)</m>, and <m>(25,0.92)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>For which cases would a one-proportion z-interval be reasonable? Explain briefly.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Why is it a problem when the sample has very few observed successes or very few observed failures?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-confidence-intervals-variance">
    <title>Confidence Intervals for a Population Variance and Standard Deviation</title>
    <shorttitle>Confidence Intervals for Variance and Standard Deviation</shorttitle>

    <p>Sometimes the main question is about spread rather than center. A
    manufacturer may want to estimate how much bottle fills vary. A coach may
    care about the variability of race times, not just the average time. In
    problems like these, the parameter of interest is the <term>population
    variance<idx><h>inference</h><h>population variance</h></idx></term>
    <m>\sigma^2</m>, or equivalently the population standard deviation
    <m>\sigma</m>.</p>

    <p>From <xref ref="sec-variance-sd-zscores"/>, the <term>sample
    variance<idx><h>summaries</h><h>sample variance</h></idx></term> is based
    on squared deviations from the sample mean. Before the data are collected,
    the random sample variance is</p>

    <me>
      S^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n (X_i-\overline{X})^2.
    </me>

    <p>After the sample is observed, its value is written <m>s^2</m>.</p>

    <p>The reason the chi-square distribution appears is that this formula is
    built from squared normal quantities. Suppose
    <m>X_1,\ldots,X_n</m> is a random sample from a normal population
    <m>N(\mu,\sigma^2)</m>. If we standardize each observation,</p>

    <me>
      Z_i=\frac{X_i-\mu}{\sigma},
    </me>

    <p>then each <m>Z_i</m> is standard normal. A sum of squares of
    independent standard normal random variables has a <term>chi-square
    distribution<idx><h>inference</h><h>chi-square
    distribution</h></idx></term>.</p>

    <p>If the population mean <m>\mu</m> were known, then</p>

    <me>
      \sum_{i=1}^n\left(\frac{X_i-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^2\sim \chi^2_n.
    </me>

    <p>But in practice <m>\mu</m> is usually unknown, so we replace it by the
    sample mean <m>\overline{X}</m>. That uses up one <term>degree of
    freedom<idx><h>inference</h><h>degrees of freedom</h></idx></term>,
    because once <m>n-1</m> of the deviations
    <m>X_i-\overline{X}</m> are known, the last one is forced by the fact that
    they add up to 0. So</p>

    <me>
      \sum_{i=1}^n\left(\frac{X_i-\overline{X}}{\sigma}\right)^2\sim \chi^2_{n-1}.
    </me>

    <p>Since</p>

    <me>
      \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i-\overline{X})^2=(n-1)S^2,
    </me>

    <p>the key result becomes</p>

    <me>
      \frac{(n-1)S^2}{\sigma^2}\sim \chi^2_{n-1}.
    </me>

    <p>That one fact is what makes a confidence interval for
    <m>\sigma^2</m> possible.</p>

    <p>The assumptions need to be stated carefully.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The data should come from a random sample or a similarly independent sampling process.</p></li>
      <li><p>The observations should be independent. If sampling is done without replacement from a finite population, a common rule of thumb is that the population should be at least 10 times as large as the sample.</p></li>
      <li><p>The population itself should be normal. This is the crucial assumption.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>That last point matters more here than it did for intervals about a
    mean. The CLT helps sample means become approximately normal for large
    samples, but it does not make the chi-square interval for variance exact.
    For variance and standard deviation, this method is justified only when
    the population distribution is normal or very close to normal.</p>

    <p>Let <m>C=1-\alpha</m>. Using the critical-value notation from
    <xref ref="app-chi-square-table"/>, where
    <m>\chi^2_{\alpha}[n-1]</m> leaves right-tail area <m>\alpha</m> for a
    chi-square distribution with <m>n-1</m> degrees of freedom, we have</p>

    <me>
      P\left(
      \chi^2_{1-\alpha/2}[n-1]
      \le
      \frac{(n-1)S^2}{\sigma^2}
      \le
      \chi^2_{\alpha/2}[n-1]
      \right)=C.
    </me>

    <p>Solving that inequality for <m>\sigma^2</m> gives the confidence
    interval for the population variance:</p>

    <me>
      \left(
      \frac{(n-1)s^2}{\chi^2_{\alpha/2}[n-1]},
      \frac{(n-1)s^2}{\chi^2_{1-\alpha/2}[n-1]}
      \right).
    </me>

    <p>If we want an interval for the population standard deviation instead,
    we simply take square roots of both endpoints:</p>

    <me>
      \left(
      \sqrt{\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\chi^2_{\alpha/2}[n-1]}},
      \sqrt{\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\chi^2_{1-\alpha/2}[n-1]}}
      \right).
    </me>

    <example xml:id="ex-ci-variance-delivery-times">
      <title>An Interval for Variation in Delivery Times</title>
      <p>Suppose delivery times on a short route are well modeled by a normal
      distribution. A random sample of 12 deliveries has sample standard
      deviation <m>s=4</m> minutes. Find a 95% confidence interval for the
      population variance and the population standard deviation.</p>

      <p>Here <m>n=12</m>, so the degrees of freedom are
      <m>n-1=11</m>. For 95% confidence, <m>\alpha=0.05</m>. From
      <xref ref="app-chi-square-table"/>,</p>

      <me>
        \chi^2_{0.025}[11]\approx 21.920
        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
        \chi^2_{0.975}[11]\approx 3.816.
      </me>

      <p>Since <m>s^2=16</m>, the variance interval is</p>

      <me>
        \left(
        \frac{11(16)}{21.920},
        \frac{11(16)}{3.816}
        \right)
        \approx
        (8.03,46.12).
      </me>

      <p>Now take square roots to get an interval for the population standard
      deviation:</p>

      <me>
        (\sqrt{8.03},\sqrt{46.12})\approx (2.83,6.79).
      </me>

      <p>So a reasonable estimate for the route-to-route spread is that the
      population standard deviation is between about 2.83 and 6.79 minutes.</p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-ci-variance-normality-warning">
      <title>Why Large Sample Size Is Not the Main Issue</title>
      <p>A researcher takes a random sample of 50 household incomes and wants
      a confidence interval for the population variance. Even though
      <m>n=50</m> is not small, household incomes are usually strongly
      right-skewed.</p>

      <p>So a chi-square interval for <m>\sigma^2</m> is not automatically
      justified. The key result
      <m>(n-1)S^2/\sigma^2\sim\chi^2_{n-1}</m> depends on a normal population,
      not just on a large sample. For variance intervals, the shape of the
      population matters a lot.</p>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="ci-inline-ex-4">
      <p>Assume a population is normal. A random sample of size 16 has sample
      variance <m>s^2=9</m>.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>What are the degrees of freedom?</p></li>
        <li><p>Write the formula for a 90% confidence interval for <m>\sigma^2</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Write the corresponding interval for <m>\sigma</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-variance-builder">
      <title>Variance Interval Builder</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Build a confidence interval for a population variance and standard deviation from a sample standard deviation.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Suppose a normal population is sampled with <m>n=15</m> and the sample standard deviation is <m>s=3.2</m>. Find the degrees of freedom.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Using the chi-square table, find a 90% confidence interval for the population variance <m>\sigma^2</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Convert the interval to a 90% confidence interval for the population standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-variance-assumption-check">
      <title>Can We Trust the Chi-Square Method?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Check the assumptions before using a confidence interval for variance.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A random sample of bolt lengths comes from a manufacturing process that is known to be close to normal. Is a chi-square interval for <m>\sigma^2</m> reasonable?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A random sample of 40 household incomes is strongly right-skewed. Should we be comfortable using the chi-square interval here? Explain.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Why does a large sample size help more for intervals about a mean than for intervals about a variance?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-sample-size-margin-error">
    <title>Margin of Error and Sample Size</title>

    <p>This section returns to the z-interval for a population mean. In that
    setting, the margin of error is</p>

    <me>
      E=z_{\alpha/2}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}.
    </me>

    <p>This formula shows two basic truths:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Higher confidence means a larger critical value and therefore a larger margin of error.</p></li>
      <li><p>Larger samples make the denominator bigger and therefore shrink the margin of error.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>If we want the margin of error to be at most some target value <m>E</m>, then we solve for <m>n</m>:</p>

    <me>
      n\ge \left(\frac{z_{\alpha/2}\sigma}{E}\right)^2.
    </me>

    <p>Since sample size must be a whole number, we always round up.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-sample-size-women-height">
      <title>Finding a Required Sample Size</title>
      
      <p>Suppose we want to estimate the mean height of women with 98%
      confidence and margin of error at most 0.5 inches. Assume <m>\sigma=2.8</m>.</p>
      
      <p>Here <m>\alpha=0.02</m>, so <m>z_{\alpha/2}=z_{0.01}=2.326</m>. Therefore</p>
      <me>
        n\ge \left(\frac{2.326(2.8)}{0.5}\right)^2\approx 169.67.
      </me>
      <p>We round up, so the least acceptable sample size is</p>
      <me>
        n=170.
      </me>
    </example>

    <p>This is one of the most practical formulas in the course. It tells
    us how much data we need before we even begin sampling.</p>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-survey-planner">
      <title>Survey Planner</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Plan a sample size before collecting data so the margin of error stays under control.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>You want to estimate the mean amount of weekly screen time with 95% confidence and margin of error at most 3 hours. Assume <m>\sigma=12</m>. Find the minimum sample size.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Suppose the margin of error is cut in half. What happens to the required sample size?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>In one sentence, explain why larger samples are useful when precision matters.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-ch10-budget-vs-precision">
      <title>Budget vs Precision</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Compare two sampling plans and decide which one gives the better estimate.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A campus poll can survey either 100 students or 196 students. If the same population standard deviation is used, which plan gives the smaller margin of error?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>If the confidence level increases from 90% to 99%, what happens to the margin of error when the sample size stays the same?</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Explain the tradeoff between wanting high confidence and wanting a small margin of error.</p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </section>

  <conclusion>
    <title>Summary</title>

    <p>Confidence intervals are built on the sampling behavior of sample means
    and sample proportions, and in one important case on sample variances as
    well.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The sampling distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> has mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma/\sqrt{n}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>The Central Limit Theorem says that for large samples, the sample mean is approximately normal.</p></li>
      <li><p>A confidence interval estimates a population parameter by giving a range of plausible values.</p></li>
      <li><p>Its basic form is point estimate plus or minus margin of error.</p></li>
      <li><p>For small samples from a normal population with unknown standard deviation, we use t critical values instead of z critical values.</p></li>
      <li><p>If <m>X\sim B(n,p)</m>, then for large samples the binomial model leads to the approximation <m>\widehat{p}\approx N\left(p,\sqrt{p(1-p)/n}\right)</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>A large-sample confidence interval for a population proportion is <m>\widehat{p}\pm z_{\alpha/2}\sqrt{\widehat{p}(1-\widehat{p})/n}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>For a normal population, <m>\frac{(n-1)S^2}{\sigma^2}\sim \chi^2_{n-1}</m>, which leads to a confidence interval for the population variance and standard deviation.</p></li>
      <li><p>The chi-square interval for variance requires a normal population; large sample size by itself is not the main justification.</p></li>
      <li><p>Sample-size formulas come from solving the margin-of-error formula for <m>n</m>.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>The next chapter turns estimation into decision-making. Instead of
    asking which parameter values are plausible, we will ask whether the
    data give strong enough evidence to reject a claimed value.</p>
  </conclusion>

  <exercises xml:id="ch10-exercises">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-1">
      <p>A population has mean 24 and standard deviation 9. A random sample of size 81 is taken.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Find the mean of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find the standard deviation of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use the CLT to state an approximate distribution for <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-2">
      <p>A sample of size 64 has mean <m>\overline{x}=41.5</m>. Assume the
      population standard deviation is known to be 8.</p> <ol>
        <li><p>Find a 95% confidence interval for the population mean.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find the margin of error.</p></li>
        <li><p>Explain what the 95% confidence level means.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-3">
      <p>Assume the population is normal. A sample of size 16 has mean
      <m>\overline{x}=12.4</m> and sample standard deviation <m>s=2.0</m>.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Write the form of the 95% t-interval for the mean.</p></li>
        <li><p>What are the degrees of freedom?</p></li> <li><p>Why is a t
        critical value used instead of a z critical value?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-4">
      <p>How large a sample is needed to estimate a population mean with 95% confidence, population standard deviation 10, and margin of error at most 2?</p>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-5">
      <p>Explain how the confidence-interval formula for a population
      proportion comes from the normal approximation to a binomial random
      variable.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Start with <m>X\sim B(n,p)</m> and write its approximate normal model for large <m>n</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use <m>\widehat{p}=X/n</m> to find the approximate mean and standard deviation of <m>\widehat{p}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Write the resulting z-based confidence-interval formula for <m>p</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-6">
      <p>In a random sample of 250 voters, 140 say they support a local park
      bond measure.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Find <m>\widehat{p}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Check whether the large-sample conditions are satisfied.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find a 95% confidence interval for the population proportion of voters who support the measure.</p></li>
        <li><p>Interpret the interval in context.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-7">
      <p>A manufacturer samples 80 batteries and finds that 6 are defective.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Is a one-proportion z-interval appropriate here? Check the large-sample conditions.</p></li>
        <li><p>If it is appropriate, find a 90% confidence interval for the population defect proportion.</p></li>
        <li><p>If it is not appropriate, explain what goes wrong with the normal approximation.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-8">
      <p>Assume a normal population. A random sample of size 12 has sample
      standard deviation <m>s=4</m>.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Find the degrees of freedom.</p></li>
        <li><p>Find a 95% confidence interval for the population variance <m>\sigma^2</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Convert the result to a 95% confidence interval for the population standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-9">
      <p>Explain carefully why the chi-square distribution appears in a
      confidence interval for a population variance.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Start with a random sample from a normal population and standardize each observation.</p></li>
        <li><p>Explain why squaring and adding leads to a chi-square distribution.</p></li>
        <li><p>Explain why replacing <m>\mu</m> by <m>\overline{X}</m> changes the degrees of freedom from <m>n</m> to <m>n-1</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ch10-ex-10">
      <p>State the assumptions for using a chi-square confidence interval for
      the population variance.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Why is independence needed?</p></li>
        <li><p>Why is normality the crucial assumption?</p></li>
        <li><p>Why does a large sample not rescue this method in the same way the CLT helps intervals for a mean?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</chapter>
